{"id":"mai-8hnc","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Delphi synthesis: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian","tags":["research","delphi-synthesis"],"body":"# Delphi Synthesis: CRDT Doc Sync with Obsidian\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAll four oracles (7 investigation tickets) converge on the same root cause: `mergeViaCRDT()` in `pkg/notes/docs.go` uses `creationBody` as the 3-way merge base forever. After the first sync, this base is stale. Every subsequent sync treats all accumulated changes — from document creation to the present — as fresh concurrent inserts from both the note peer and the file peer. Since those diffs are nearly identical and both treated as concurrent, the CRDT correctly (but unhelpfully) preserves both sets, causing duplication. Each sync compounds the problem, producing exponential growth: 2 → 4 → 8 → 16 → 32 occurrences of repeated fragments. The function `lastSyncBody()` carries the right name and a TODO comment, but returns `\"\"` and is never called — a smoking gun the authors knew this was missing.\n\nThe CRDT layer itself (yrs/WASM) is not buggy. Obsidian is not the root cause — it is a frequency amplifier. The corruption reproduces with plain `SyncDocs()` calls and no daemon, no Obsidian, no special save behavior. The daemon atomic-save debouncing is a separate, already-fixed issue.\n\nThe primary design disagreement between oracles is whether to keep the CRDT in the sync path. After weighing the evidence, the recommended fix keeps the CRDT but gives it the correct merge base — a smaller, lower-risk change with higher payoff than a full replacement.\n\n---\n\n## Convergent Findings\n\nThese findings were reached independently by every oracle (high confidence):\n\n| Finding | Evidence |\n|---------|----------|\n| `mergeViaCRDT()` uses `creationBody` as base on every sync | `docs.go:549`: `base := creationBody` never updated |\n| `lastSyncBody()` is dead code — returns `\"\"`, never called | `docs.go:520`: TODO + return `\"\"` |\n| Duplication is exponential (2^N pattern) | Reproduced independently: 2, 4, 8, 16, 32 occurrences |\n| The CRDT layer (yrs/WASM) is correct | All existing CRDT tests pass; merge semantics are working as designed |\n| Bug reproduces without Obsidian, daemon, or special save behavior | Oracles 1 and 2 reproduced with direct `SyncDocs()` calls |\n| Obsidian is a frequency amplifier, not the root cause | ~2s autosave triggers the broken merge path repeatedly |\n| Atomic save / fsnotify are separate issues already fixed | `9c6e6bb` fixed daemon delete debouncing |\n| Existing tests are too weak | `Contains()` checks instead of exact body assertions; no repeated-save cycles |\n| The fix requires tracking the last-synced content as the merge base | All oracles proposed some form of `lastSyncBody` |\n\n---\n\n## Divergent Findings\n\n### 1. Keep CRDT vs. Replace with 3-way Text Merge\n\n**Oracles 1 \u0026 2 (GPT-5.4):** Recommend dropping CRDT from `SyncDocs`, replacing with tracked `last_sync_body` + 3-way text merge. Rationale: Obsidian provides whole-file snapshots, not CRDT operations; once you are doing snapshot-to-snapshot diffs, you have a classic 3-way merge problem.\n\n**Oracles 3 \u0026 4 (Claude Opus 4.6):** Recommend keeping the CRDT, fixing only the merge base (~20–50 line change). Rationale: CRDT already built and working; handles character-level concurrent edits without conflict markers; fix is simpler; infrastructure is already correct.\n\n**Why the divergence:** Different cost/benefit assessments of the CRDT infrastructure. Oracles 1/2 value simplicity of removing the WASM dependency from the file sync path; Oracles 3/4 value the concurrent-edit correctness and future-proofing.\n\n**Resolution:** Both camps require the same core fix — tracking `lastSyncBody`. Keeping the CRDT is the lower-risk path: ~50 lines instead of replacing the entire merge mechanism, preserves concurrent-edit correctness for the rare case where both note and file change between syncs, and avoids introducing a new text-merge dependency.\n\n### 2. How to Track the Last-Sync Base\n\n- Oracle 1/2: `last_sync_body` stored as a metadata event or note-level file\n- Oracle 3 (fczb): Use `YDoc.Content()` as base (elegant for single-editor case, breaks when note also changed since sync)\n- Oracle 3 (t1i8): Store a `ydoc-sync` checkpoint event separating the sync-time YDoc from the live YDoc\n- Oracle 4 (q7me): Shadow sidecar files in `.maitake/shadows/`\n- Oracle 4 (l4ec): Add `lastsync` event to the note's event stream (body = merged content)\n\n**Resolution:** The event-stream approach (`lastsync` event) is the best fit for maitake's event-sourced architecture. It stores the merged body in the note's own history, survives daemon restarts, and requires no external files.\n\n### 3. How to Handle True Concurrent Edits (Both Sides Changed Since Sync)\n\n- Oracles 1/2: Surface a conflict; do not silently merge; produce conflict file or conflict note\n- Oracles 3/4: CRDT merges both small diffs from the correct base automatically; character-level interleaving is acceptable\n\n**Resolution:** If the CRDT is kept (recommended), it handles this case automatically and correctly — both sets of changes are preserved, no conflict markers needed in the markdown.\n\n---\n\n## Unique Discoveries\n\n| Oracle | Unique Discovery |\n|--------|-----------------|\n| Oracle 1 (kqnz) | End-to-end `SyncDocs()` repro in a temp repo, confirming exact 2^N growth |\n| Oracle 1 (kqnz) | `SyncDocs()` emits TWO ydoc update events per sync (one from `Append(body)` → `updateYDoc`, one from `SyncDocs` itself) |\n| Oracle 2 (b955) | Existing test assertions use `Contains()` — test passes even when merged body is wrong |\n| Oracle 2 (b955/kjyq) | Note-side YDoc DOES advance (via `updateYDoc`), but file-side peer reconstruction ignores this shared history |\n| Oracle 3 (fczb) | `YDoc.Content()` at load time equals the last-synced content — but only if note has not been independently edited since sync |\n| Oracle 3 (t1i8) | Cycle-by-cycle trace showing how the snowball compounds: each merge re-encodes already-merged content as new concurrent inserts |\n| Oracle 4 (q7me) | Shadow sidecar approach enables conditional CRDT use: only invoke CRDT for true concurrent edits; simpler path for file-only or note-only changes |\n| Oracle 4 (l4ec) | Correct CRDT merge pattern: `filePeer.Load(state.YDocState)` + `noteOps := Diff(lastSync, noteBody)` + `fileOps := Diff(lastSync, fileContent)` — both peers start from the SAME loaded state |\n\n---\n\n## Composite Answer: The Fix\n\n### Recommended: Keep CRDT, Fix the Merge Base via `lastsync` Event\n\nThe fix has three parts:\n\n**Part 1: Emit `lastsync` Event After Every Successful Sync**\n\nAfter `SyncDocs` successfully writes a merged body to both disk and note, append:\n\n```go\nengine.Append(AppendOptions{\n    TargetID: id,\n    Kind:     \"event\",\n    Field:    \"lastsync\",\n    Body:     mergedBody,\n})\n```\n\n**Part 2: Implement `lastSyncBody()`**\n\n```go\nfunc lastSyncBody(state *State) string {\n    for i := len(state.Events) - 1; i \u003e= 0; i-- {\n        e := state.Events[i]\n        if e.Kind == \"event\" \u0026\u0026 e.Field == \"lastsync\" {\n            return e.Body\n        }\n    }\n    return \"\" // falls back to creationBody in caller\n}\n```\n\n**Part 3: Fix the Merge Base in `mergeViaCRDT()`**\n\n```go\n// Before:  base := creationBody\n// After:\nbase := lastSyncBody(state)\nif base == \"\" {\n    base = creationBody // correct for the very first sync\n}\n```\n\n**Why This Approach Wins**\n\n| Criterion | Fix base (recommended) | Drop CRDT |\n|-----------|------------------------|-----------|\n| Lines changed | ~50 | ~300+ |\n| Risk | Low | Medium |\n| Concurrent edit handling | Character-level, automatic | Conflict markers |\n| New dependencies | None | diff-match-patch or similar |\n| Event-sourced alignment | Yes (lastsync event) | Yes |\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Category 1: Regression Tests (Must-Haves)\n\n1. **`TestSyncDocs_RepeatedFullFileSaves_NoContentGrowth`** — Create note, materialize, 10 Obsidian-style full-file rewrites with small appended changes, `SyncDocs` after each. Assert: final note body matches file exactly; no fragment repeated more than once; body length is O(N) not O(2^N).\n\n2. **`TestMergeViaCRDT_StaleCreationBase_NoDuplication`** — Create note \"A\", edit note 5× to grow it, call `mergeViaCRDT` with fileContent = \"A...F\" (one new line). Assert: output = \"A...F\", no duplication.\n\n3. **`TestSyncDocs_LastSyncBodyAdvances`** — Sync, verify `lastSyncBody()` returns merged body; sync again with new file edit, verify it returns new merged body.\n\n### Category 2: Unit Tests for Merge Logic\n\n4. File-only change → file content applied to note\n5. Note-only change → note written to file\n6. Non-overlapping concurrent edits → both preserved\n7. Overlapping concurrent edits → CRDT resolves, no duplication\n8. Large document (~5000 words), small edit → output ≤ 110% expected size\n9. Unicode / emoji / CJK text through full merge cycle\n10. Idempotence: two syncs with no changes = no-op\n11. Convergence: after any successful sync, `note.Body == file.Content`\n\n### Category 3: Integration Tests Simulating Obsidian\n\n12. `TestObsidian_FrequentSaves` — 20 saves with small increments, no duplication\n13. `TestObsidian_AgentAndUserConcurrent` — Agent appends section while user edits another; both present after sync\n14. `TestObsidian_DaemonRestart` — Sync, restart daemon, edit file, sync again; `lastsync` base persists\n15. `TestObsidian_AtomicSave` — Remove + Create sequence; no tombstone, no corruption\n16. `TestObsidian_LargeDoc_SmallEdit` — 2700-word document, one-line edit; output stays ~2700 words\n\n### Category 4: Adversarial / Property Tests\n\n17. Content bounded: After N sync cycles, body length ≤ 2× expected; never O(2^N)\n18. No-op stability: N syncs with no changes → N identical states\n19. 100-cycle stability: 100 rounds alternating note/file edits; content never balloons\n20. Fuzz: Random sequences of note edits + file rewrites; no substring appears more times than input contains it\n\n### Test Repairs Needed in Current Suite\n\n- Strengthen `TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged` to assert exact merged body, not just `Contains(\"File edit\")`\n- Add exact-body assertions wherever `Contains()` currently appears in docs tests\n\n---\n\n## Confidence Assessment\n\n| Claim | Confidence | Basis |\n|-------|-----------|-------|\n| Root cause: `creationBody` as stale merge base | Very High | 4 oracles reproduced independently; direct code evidence |\n| Bug reproduces without Obsidian or daemon | Very High | Oracles 1 and 2 ran direct `SyncDocs()` calls |\n| The CRDT layer (yrs) is correct | High | All CRDT unit tests pass; merge semantics match documented behavior |\n| Exponential (2^N) growth pattern | High | Directly reproduced; matches known Yjs duplication pattern |\n| `lastsync` event approach fixes the bug | High | Logically sound; Oracle 4 (l4ec) sketched the precise implementation |\n| Keeping CRDT is better than replacing it | Medium-High | Value judgment; depends on future plans for collaborative editing |\n| Obsidian autosaves every ~2 seconds | Medium | Plugin docs confirm; no official Obsidian engineering spec |\n\n---\n\n## Recommended Actions\n\n1. **Implement the `lastsync` event** — emit after each successful `SyncDocs` write\n2. **Implement `lastSyncBody()`** — fold state to find latest `lastsync` event body\n3. **Fix `mergeViaCRDT()`** — use `lastSyncBody(state)` as base, fall back to `creationBody` only on first sync\n4. **Add regression test** `TestSyncDocs_RepeatedFullFileSaves_NoContentGrowth` before shipping\n5. **Strengthen existing tests** that use `Contains()` to assert exact merged body\n6. **Audit `updateYDoc` call paths** — confirm YDoc is updated on every note body change\n7. **Fix the dual ydoc event issue** — `SyncDocs` emits two ydoc updates per sync; consolidate to one authoritative source\n8. **Consider storing `lastsync-ydoc`** — the merged YDoc state at sync time — to enable correct CRDT merge for the concurrent-edit case\n\n---\n\n## Appendix: Oracle Contributions\n\n| Oracle | Key Contribution |\n|--------|-----------------|\n| Oracle 1 (mai-kqnz, GPT-5.4) | End-to-end temp-repo reproduction confirming exact 2^N duplication; identified dual ydoc event emission as secondary issue |\n| Oracle 2 (mai-b955 + mai-kjyq, GPT-5.4) | Reproduced without daemon using direct API; identified test weakness (`Contains()` assertions); clearest articulation of asymmetry between note-side YDoc (advances) and file-side reconstruction (ignores shared history) |\n| Oracle 3 initial (mai-t1i8, Claude Opus 4.6) | Cycle-by-cycle snowball trace; introduced the checkpoint vs. live YDoc distinction |\n| Oracle 3 refined (mai-fczb, Claude Opus 4.6) | Cleanest fix sketch (~20 lines): use `ydocContent` as base; confirmed CRDT is misused not broken; recommended keeping CRDT |\n| Oracle 4 (mai-q7me, Claude Opus 4.6) | Shadow sidecar design with conditional CRDT use; 18-test testing strategy |\n| Oracle 4 alt (mai-l4ec, Claude Opus 4.6) | Most detailed implementation: `lastsync` event in event stream; correct peer construction pattern; ~50 line estimate |","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:29:28Z","branch":"main"}
